I think a lot about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to also critically see them.
We grew up in a golden age of media with a collective consciousness for pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to wonder where they came from, because back then you couldn't easily determine that anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we put them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and have influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong nostalgia.
We used to order pizza every Thursday when "The Office" was still on and watch the series together.
That was quite different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it and posts social media posts with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Unconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us are still watching series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman", in which so many one-liners appeared that would be memes today.
We brought all these catchphrases and assumed most people already understood them.
Today, one can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it's massively spreading virally.
There's just too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this oversaturation?
We're trapped in a vicious cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to find out that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we have to hold on to our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that we liked can also have made big mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on one or the other on the way there.
Since we have lost our collective consciousness in terms of media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
We are in a phase of transformation and I am curious to see what it will come down to in the end.
